ce:section.ce:para:
It is worth to mention that the gas sensing properties were affected by the surface area of materials applied in the sensor applications. Fig. 2
                         displays the adsorption-desorption behavior of both MgO and CDots@MgO nano-particles, which shows the (IV isotherm) for both samples. This behavior refers to the existence of meso-porous structure. As seen, BET surface area of the CDots@MgO is larger than that of MgO. It is worth to mention also that materials with large specific surface areas have an advantageous increasing gas sensing performance. (Table 1
                        ) presents all the texture parameters of the BET analysis for both samples.

The effect of temperature on the Schottky barrier height and the response of the fabricated device sensors were studied when exposed to constant stream of 120 ppm of H2S gas (Fig. 9
                        a,b). As shown, the decline in the barrier height was obtained until the (Tapplied
                        ) reached 200 °C for CDots@MgO and 400 °C for MgO. This decline in the Schottky barrier height produces an increase in H2S adsorption rate on the sensor surfaces and hence increasing the response. As seen, the lower barrier height showing a higher response. Although the barrier height is less for MgO than CDots@MgO while sensing response of MgO is also less. This behavior can be attributed to the decoration of CDots on the surface of MgO where the CDots have functionalized groups on their surfaces, see our previous work [33–38]. These functionalized groups play a role in capturing the electrons from the adsorbed H2S gas and form the conductive networks and hence increasing the conductivity of the sensor which is reflected in the sensor response [54–56].
